<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="un2003e"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="un2" href="#un2003">UN2: </a>  <a href="../../FF/unbs/un2all.htm#un2003e"> (VI.D.7) 3(e)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> ~ was again in the field but he had a stronger opposition to face than a 12 month ago when the infirm Rising Glass was the best of his three opponents. He had to meet this time Zinfandel and Sceptre, who had been first &amp; second in the Coronation Cup at Epsom and as he had not shown to advantage in France this season he had very few friends, the race being regarded as a match between the 2 others; ~</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">THE ASCOT MEETING, Thursday. <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> <br>The third race on the card was the Gold Cup, for which Maximum, winner last year, <mark>was again in the field, but he had a stronger opposition to face than a twelvemonth ago, when the infirm Rising Glass was the best of his three opponents. He had to meet this time Zinfandel and Sceptre, who had been first and second in the Coronation Cup at Epsom and, as he had not shown to advantage in France this season, he had very few friends, the race being regarded as a match between the two others;</mark> for little or no attention was paid to the fourth runner, Throwaway, whose chances were regarded as so remote that odds of 20 to one were offered against him. <small> <a name="TT17jun04" href="/udra/udex.htm#TT17jun04"><cite title="source">The Times</cite></a> (London, 17 June 1904), 12/1</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c16234d" href="../../../F/FF/fnbs/c16all.htm#c16234d">VI.C.16:234(d)</a>, <a name="c16235a" href="../../../F/FF/fnbs/c16all.htm#c16235a">VI.C.16:235(a)</a> </dd> </dd></dl>
